{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hawthorne_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205698267/1938031801/0995.xml":{"full_text":"HOUSING PROGRAM\nBEGINS TO PERK UP\nNEWS BEHIND THE NEWS\nBy PAUL MALLON\n(WwM Copyright. by King F.\u00bbture. Syndicate. Inc. All Right.\nRMervad. Reproduction In Full or in Part Strictly Prohibited.)\nLEFT-HANDED pallbearers of the New Deal are stand\ning in line waiting for the housing program to sink,\nhoping for the worst. But, unfortunately for them, the\nanemic Government idea is showing new signs of life.\nLatest figures reveal small\nbut continuous increases in the\namount of mortgages accepted\nFMI Midtea\nfor appraisal\non dwellings\nsince the first\nof the year.\nPast three\nweeks have\nrun above\nlast year for\nthe first time.\nLast figure is\n*20,38 6,000\nfor the week\nending March\n12 which com\npares very\nfavorably\nwith $14,176,-\n000 the same\nweek last year. Additional\nactivity in the large scale pro\nject field also is being re\nported.\nLikewise the Straus low-cost\ncity improvement plan is be\nginning to show Initial results,\ndespite the fact that Mr. Straus\nIs virtually surrounded by\nInterior Secretary Ickes.\nThe pallbearers, however,\nare consoling themselves with\nthe supposition that it cannot\nlast. ___\nMITHAT makes them so impa\nir tient is they all have bigger\nIf not better plans which they\nwant Mr. Roosevelt to espouse.\nThese proposals have been\nkept confidential, but some are\ntoo large to be tied securely.\nThe Hopkins organization in\nWPA, for instance, has two\nwhich may stretch the bounds\nof your imagination. Most ex\npansive (and perhaps most ex\npensive to taxpayers) is one pro\nposing that the Government just\nbuild houses with WPA money\nand labor. Presumably the Gov\nernment would acquire land, buy\nmaterials and sell houses (if pos\nsible), thus making itself the\nbiggest monopoly in the real\nestate business outside of Russia.\nMore moderate is a second\nWPA plan just to put the Gov\nernment into subdivision devel\nopment subsidies by donating\nfree WPA labor for building\nstreets, sewers, waterpipes, etc.,\nfor private speculative real\nestate ventures.\nAnother high official is advo\ncating in inner councils the\nproposition of just giving away\n20 per cent of the cost to anyone\nwho wants a home. Directors of\nthe Federal Home Loan Bank\nBoard also have a confidential\nbill providing some sort of a sub\nsidy. Then there is talk of tax\nexemptions for building con\nstruction which seems to be the\nmildest of the lot.\nFHA naturally Is opposing\nthese ideas on the ground\nthat they would drive private\ncapital out of real estate and\ninjure existing values. So is the\nTreasury.\nBut the potential housing pro\ngram pallbearers are still hope\nful one of these schemes will be\nthe spending program which Mr.\nRoosevelt may be inclined to\ntake up if business does not im\nprove within the next 30 to 60\ndays.\nAs advocates of spending they\nconfidentially expect larger sums\nof Government credit (there Is\nHULL PROTESTS\nTARIFF ON PORK\n(IN.S.) Secretary of State Hull\ntoday lodged with the Senate\nFinance Committee chairman a\nvigorous protest against the 6\ncents a pound excise tax which\nthe House imposed on imports of\npork in the pending tax bill.\nHull asserted the proposal ini\nthe long run would seriously in\njure the corn hog industry through\nreciprocal trade treaties. Further\nmore. he added, even were pork\nimports to remain at the unusually\nhigh figure of last year, the tax\nstill would not bring this Govern\nment the $5,000,000 revenue esti\nmated.\nHull advised Senator Pat Harri\nson, Finance Committee chairman,\nthat if the Senate did not knock\nout the House imposed tax trade\nwith Poland would be sharply cur\ntailed.\n\u201cThere is no more dangerous\ngame,\" he said, \u201cthan an em\nbargo policy in foreign trade.\nOther countries are encouraged\nand, in fact, compelled to act\nin the same way toward Ameri\ncan exports.\u201d\nRyerson Renamed\nAs Yale Fellow\nNEW HAVEN, Conn., March 18\n(IJi.S.).\u2014Edward L. Ryerson, jr\u201e\nof Chicago, today was assured of a\nsecond term as an alumni fellow\nof Tale Corporation, the trustee\nboard of the university.\nHe was unanimously Indorsed\nby the alumni board to succeed\nhimself for the six-year term,\n1938-44. according to John Mar\nshal Holcombe, jr\u201e chairman of\nthe board.\nTcf.pAona XEpaMta J 234\nno money) will have to be spent\nand, of course, each ohe wants\nto be in charge of it.\nNo reason exists to believe\nthe White House has such a\nview. Mr. Roosevelt has indi\ncated he expects to recommend\nnothing new before adjourn\nment.\nHowever, all sides are waiting\nI to see what happens in business.\nON one point the pallbearers\nhave fairly firm basis for\nhope. Existing Government ac-\nI tivities are not hitting on all\ncylinders and are not generally\nexpected to furnish enough im\npetus for building revival.\nI For example, the new amend\nments sought to encourage na\ntional mortgage associations.\nBut only one such association\nhas been formed, and that one\nwith RFC capital here in Wash\nington.\nTrouble is the Housing Ad\nministrator has dictatorial pow\ner pver the associations and\nmay dissolve them if he thinks\nthey are conducting themselves\nin an \u201cunsafe\u201d or \u201cunbusiness\nlike\u201d manner.\nANOTHER quasi-dictatorship\ntreading the primrose Mus\nsolini-Hitler path to the poor\nhouse is Japan.\nLatest trusted figures to reach\nthose on high here indicate the\nJapanese national debt has now\nreached the total of its annual\nnational income. (Our debt is a\nlittle more than half our in\ncome.) The current Japanese\ndebt figure is 13,115 million\nyen, which is more than double\nthe debt of seven years ago,\n5,956 million in 1931.\nThe reason is simple. The\nJapanese people cannot afford\nto pay for conquest by taxa\ntion. The government has al\nready squeezed them dry. The\nonly way the government can\nget the money to conquer China\nis by loading the banks with\ngovernment debt.\nrpHEIR current budget is 7,667\nA million yen, of which 4,800\nmillion (about two-thirds), is\nfor extra military and naval\nexpenditures.\nBut the real extent of their\nweakness is shown in the fact\nthat they are planning to raise\n5,200 millions of the 7,667 mil\nlions by bonds. In other words,\nthey expect to get only 2,467\nmillions by taxation and drain\nthe rest from the banks, which\nhold the people\u2019s money.\nIncidentally, their total emer\ngency expenditures for the last\ntwo years have amounted to\n7.4 billion yen. With a 29 cent\nyen, you might therefore roughly\nestimate the cost of her con\nquest of China at about $2,146,-\n000,000.\nHow long she can continue\nto defy the law of gravity by\ntricks of sharp dictatorial econ\nomy, no one here now will guess.\nFirst sign of the end will come\nin Japan, as in Italy and Ger\nmany, when prices get out from\nunder the government thumb\nand rise sharply.\nFrom the inside, dictating\ndoes not seem to be as profit\nable a business as the glories of\ncurrent conquests indicate.\nVISITOR TO 0. C.\nDIES ON STREET\nA man, identified from cards in\nhis wallet as Charles F. Andersen,\nPine Grove, Pa\u201e fell dead today\nin the 1300 block of New York Ave.\nN. W. He was about 65 years old.\nPolice said he had a bus ticket\nto Lebanon. Pa., and arrived in\nI Washington early this morning\nfrom Richmond. He was coming\nNorth, they said, from High Point,\nN. C.\nDr. Otis Snyder, of Emergency\nHospital, pronounced the man\ndead and the body was removed\nto the District Morgue. A. C. An\nderson was registered March 11 at\nthe Annapolis Hotel, indicating\nthat he passed through Washing\nton at that time.\nMother of Victim\nOs Drink, Auto Sue\nCHICAGO. March 18 (1.N.5.).\nSuit for $175,000, the largest sum\never sought under the Illinois\ndram shop act, was on file today\nin circuit court at Geneva.\nMrs. Alta M. Waidley, of Aurora,\nasks that amount from three\nsaloonkeepers who, she charged,\nsold liquor to Royce Brooke. 20,\nher son. Brooke was killed when\nhe smashed his rented automobile\ninto a tree.\nDIVIDEND OMITTED\nNEW YORK, March 18 (1.N.5.).\nBriggs Manufacturing Company\ndirectors today omitted a dividend\nat this time \u201cdue to current op\nerations and continuing uncer\ntainty as to the near-term business\noutlook.\u201d On March 31, last year,\na dividend of 50 cents was voted\non the common.\nBut\u2014\nSay 8 Boake Carter\nPropaganda groups, i hear,\nare due for an overhauling\nin Congress. As a general rule.\nit is an excel\nlent thing to\ncast the glare\nof the. spot\nlight on such\ngroups. But\nunfortunate\nly, all too\noften, investi\ngations turn\nout to be\nmerely coun\nter propagan\nda' Rather\nthan attempt\ning to do a\ntechnical, im\npartial job of\nBoako Carter\nexposition, more often they are\nsimply retaliatory moves by\npoliticians or opposing social\nforces and minorities.\nHence the investigations pro\nduce propaganda just as bad as\nthat which the inquisitors are\nsupposed to be engaged in ex\nposing.\nA favorite trick is to try and\nsmear, or pin the onus to, for\neign-born American citizens and\nascribe to them underhand and\nulterior motives in things they\nmay say or do. A lie gathers\nsuch momentum that truth is\nhard beset to catch it.\n\nUNLUCKY SMEARED\nrthe unlucky victim happens\nto be foreign-born, the merits\nof his arguments are not met\nand knocked dowh with facts.\nHe is simply \"smeared\u201d with\nwell-planted stories that he is a\n\"spy.\u201d\nIt is therefore not without\nsome amusement and ireny that\nwe find that there are 24 mem\nbers of the current Congress\nwho are foreign-born.\nAdolph Sabath, Democrat,\nChicago, was born in Zabori,\nBohemia, now Czechoslovakia,\nin 1866. He came to this coun\ntry in 1881 and took out his\nown papers.\nNoah Morgan Mason, Repub\nlican, Oglesby, 81., was bom in\nWales and came here at the\nage of 8. His citizenship is\nderivative, carrying his father\u2019s\npapers. Pehr G. Holmes, Repub\nlican, Worcester. Mass., was\nborn in Sweden, 1881; took out\nhis papers after coming here\nabout the age of 6. John\nToussaint Bernard, Farmer-\nLabor, Eleveth, Minn., born in\nCorsica, 1893, came here when\n14, citizenship derivative. Sen\nator James E. Murray, Democrat,\nButte, Mont., bom in Canada,\n1876, coming here in 1900 and\ntaking out his papers. Karl\nStefan, Republican, Norfolk,\nNeb., born Bohemia-Austria,\n1884, came here when 2 and\ncitizenship, therefore, derivative.\nMORE FOREIGN BORN\nCHARLES D. BINDERUP,\nDemocrat, Minden, Neb.,\nI Sydney Selinger Says. 1\n\"When you buy diamond*\u2014 Bg\nknow your jrwiltr. For over\nJ* a half century thi* ttore ha*\nbeen famou* for the quality\nand \u25a0\u2022lection of it* dia\nmond*. I have made per\ntonal buying trip* to Amtter\ndam and other leading\nmarket* to atture Selinger\ncuttomer* the in dia-\nmond value*.\u201d\nI A Most Extraordinary\nI DIAMOND VALUE 1\niMal\nKfl!\n8 Diamond Engagement Pair\nS4O VcZue both tings for\n1 29.85\nPAY ONLY $1 WEEKLY\nSuperbly matched and ttyled. Choice of white or yel\nlow 14 kt. gold. S genuine diamond* in wedding ring/\nitunning engagement ring with large center diamond\nand 2 tide diamond,. BOTH RINGS AT A PRICE i\nI YOU EXPECT TO PAY FOR ONE.\n\u201cIT\u2019S SOMEBODY\u2019S\nBIRTHDAY TODAY\"\n1 SeliMger's I\nI 818 F STIfeET N.W. I\nwk Credit Jewelers IK Loot for the fig\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES, FRIDAY, MARCH 18, 1938\nBoake Carter\u2019s opinion! are\nhis own and not necessarily\nthose of The Washington\nTinies.\nborn Denmark, 1874, parents\nhomesteading to the United\nStates when he was 6 months\nold. Citizenship derivative. Wil\nliam B. Barry, Brooklyn, Demo\ncrat, bom Ireland, 1902, citizen\nship derivative, as he came as\na minor. Herman Paul Koppel\nman. bom 1880, Odessa, Rus\nsia, coming here when two years\nold. Charles Eaton, Republican,\nPlainfield, N. J. Born Nova\nScotia, 1868, coming here 1888,\ntook out own papers. Harold\nKnutson, Republican, St. Cloud,\nMinn., born Norway, 1880, com\ning here 1886, citizenship deriva\ntive. Robert Ramsey, Democrat,\nFallonsbee, W. Va., bom Dur\nham, England, 1877, arriving as\nbaby citizenship de r i vative.\nJohn McGrath, San Mateo Cal.,\nDemocrat, bom Ireland 1877;\ncame here at 17, took out own\npapers. Leonard Schuetz. Chi\ncago, Democrat, boro Posen,\nGermany! now Poland), in 1887,\ncame to the United States, 1888,\ncitizenship derivative.\n\nROBERT CROSSER, Cleve\nland, Democrat, bom Scot\nland, 1874, coming here at age\nof 7, citizenship derivative. B.\nJ. Behrmann, Progressive, Mel\nlen, Wls., born Germany, 1880,\nentered United States at 13,\ntook out own papers. Anthony\nFlegler, Parma, Ohio, Democrat,\nbom 1900 ta part of Austria\nnow Rumania, citizenship de\nrivative as entered as baby.\nSenator James J. Davis, Pitts\nburgh, Pa., Republican, bom\nWales, 1873, entered 1881, cit\nizenship derivative. Vincent\nPalmisano, Baltimore, Md\u201e\nDemocrat, Italy, 1883, came here\nat age 2. Michael Stack, Phila\ndelphia, Democrat, came from\nIreland in 1903 and took out\nown papers. Sam Dickstein,\nNew York, Democrat, bom In\nRussia, 1885, came here age 3,\ncitizenship derivative. Albert\nRutherford, Honesdale, Pa., Re\npublican, bom in Canada, 1875,\nFrank Crowther,\u2019 Schenectady,\nN. Y., Republican, bom in Eng\nland. 1870. Senator Robert F.\nWagner, New York, Democrat,\nfather of the Wagner Act, bom\n1887 in Germany, coming to\nUnited States when boy of 9.\nBy the rales of the smear\ncampaigners of Washington,\nthey\u2019d better take care to look\nover their shoulders when they\nwalk to the office every morn\ning!\n(Copyright. ledger Syndicate)\n(Boake Carter\u2019s opinions are\nhis own and not necessarily\nthose of The Washington\nTimes.)\nPTA~CARD PARTY\nThe P.-T. A. of the Henry D.\nCooke School will hold its annual\ncard oarty in the school audi\ntorium tonight at 8 o\u2019clock.\nExclusive with\nThe Hecht Co.!\nTHI